#Text=Roger Jones , 1st Viscount Ranelagh
#Text=Roger Jones , 1st Viscount Ranelagh
#Text=PC ( Ire )
#Text=( before 1589 [ 1 ] – 1643 ) was a member of the Peerage of Ireland and lord president of Connaught .
#Text=He was Chief Leader of the Army and Forces of Connaught during the early years of the Irish Confederate Wars .
#Text=In addition to Viscount Ranelagh , he held the title Baron Jones of Navan .
#Text=Jones was the only son of the Archbishop of Dublin and Lord Chancellor of Ireland , Thomas Jones , and his wife Margaret Purdon .
#Text=He was knighted at Drogheda on 24 March 1607 . [ 1 ]
#Text=In 1609 , he married Frances Moore , the daughter of Sir Garret Moore , 1st Viscount Moore of Drogheda and Mary Colley . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]
#Text=Jones was a member of the Parliament of Ireland for the borough of Trim in County Meath from 1613 to 1615 .
#Text=In 1620 , he was named to the privy council of Ireland .
#Text=He was the Chief Leader of the Army and Forces of Connaught and was Vice President of Connaught from 1626 . [ 1 ]
#Text=In 1608 his father became involved in a bitter feud with Christopher St Lawrence , 10th Baron Howth , in which Roger also became embroiled .
#Text=His reference to Howth as a brave man among cowards was enough to provoke his opponent , a notoriously quarrelsome man , to violence .
#Text=In the spring of 1609 , Jones , Howth and their followers engaged in a violent fracas at a tennis court in Thomas Street , Dublin , and a Mr. Barnewall was killed .
#Text=The Lord Deputy of Ireland , Sir Arthur Chichester , an enemy of Howth , had him arrested immediately , though he was never brought to trial .
#Text=On 25 August 1628 , Jones was created Baron Jones of Navan and 1st Viscount Ranelagh by King Charles I . [ 1 ]
#Text=He was made Lord President of Connaught on 11 September 1630 to serve alongside Charles Wilmot , 1st Viscount Wilmot . [ 3 ]
#Text=Jones was killed in battle against Confederate forces under the leadership of Owen Roe O'Neill in 1643 . [ 4 ]
#Text=Family
#Text=The 1st Viscount Ranelagh was married twice .
#Text=1st wife : Frances Moore ( daughter of Garret Moore , 1st Viscount Moore of Drogheda ) and Mary Colley , daughter of Sir Henry Colley .
#Text=Several children of the 1st Viscount Ranelagh maintained the family 's prominence : [ 1 ]
#Text=Arthur Jones , 2nd Viscount Ranelagh

#Text=, married Lady Catherine Boyle , who was the daughter of Richard Boyle , 1st Earl of Cork , and also the older sister of pioneering chemist Robert Boyle , and the writer Mary Rich , Countess of Warwick .
#Text=Lady Margaret Jones , married John Clotworthy , 1st Viscount Massereene .
#Text=Mary Jones , married firstly Lieutenant Colonel John Chichester , son of Edward Chichester , 1st Viscount Chichester .
#Text=Their son Arthur Chichester , 2nd Earl of Donegall inherited the earldom from his uncle .
#Text=After his death she remarried Colonel Christopher Copley of Wadworth , and had further issue .
#Text=Thomas Jones , whose descendants reclaimed the Ranelagh Viscountcy after a period of dormancy following the death of Richard Jones , 1st Earl of Ranelagh .

#Text=Second wife : Catherine Longueville ( daughter of Sir Henry Longueville , of Wolverton , co. Buckingham and his wife Katherine Cary , sister of Henry Cary , 1st Viscount of Falkland ) , by whom he had issue :
#Text=Elizabeth Jones ( married Col. Robert Sandys , son of Sir Edwin Sandys . ) [ 5 ]
